ary partnerships exemplify an approach to governing which is based on networks (as distinct from hierarchies and markets)? Partnerships, New Labour and the governance of welfare: provides an up-to-date critical analysis of partnerships; addresses the highly topical theme of 'partnerships' as the means of achieving joined-up government; presents empirical evidence from a wide range of welfare partnerships; examines the relationships between local welfare partnerships and the management of those partnerships by central government; reveals the imbalance of power which characterises many contemporary partnerships. ·  It is essential reading for academics and students of contemporary social and public policy and for those with an interest in networks and other theories of welfare governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 0aPublic-private sector cooperationzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAlcock, Pete, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Jonathan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Marny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aExworthy, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGewirtz, Sharon, econtri